AGI - The Ministry of Development and Social Inclusion of Peru informs that it has started the procedures > to present the case of the elderly Marcelino Abad in the Guinness of primates, > so that it can be recognized as the oldest person in the world > for having completed, according to official documents, for a few days 124 years >. So far the oldest man ever was the Venezuelan Juan Vicente Perez, who died in 2022 at the age of 114 years, and currently the oldest is the English John Tinniswood, at 111 years and 223 days. The Spanish Maria Branyas Moreira, who has just turned 117, holds the record of a woman and the oldest in the world.
&nbsp;
Abad obtained his first identity document in 2019, when he was localized by the staff of the social program Pension 65, in the province of Ambo>, and from 2022 he resides in the house 'Mis Abuelitos', along with 28 elders. "With great pride, Marcelino confessed that one of his secrets to keep healthy and optimistic is to eat the fruits that nature offers him, even if he likes to eat mutton meat. Chew leaves of coca, as a habit he acquired during his working days," he told the ministry.
&nbsp;
Abad explained that the secret of its longevity is to have a quiet life and a healthy diet. The Huanuqueno, who according to official documents was born in 1900, remained orphaned at the age of 7, lived in rural areas and learned "to benefit from the benefits of nature" to develop a healthy lifestyle that led him to blow off the 124 candles on April 5.
